From cou.: 0 Journal
From Soup: 0 Phys. Chem. Chem. Phys.
 ###### 
From cou.: 1 We report non-resonant inelastic X-ray scattering experiments of several gaseous samples in the inner-shell excitation energy range. The experimental near-edge spectra from all the K-edges of N2, N2O, and CO2 including the momentum transfer dependence are presented. The results are analyzed using density functional theory calculations that accurately reproduce the experimental spectral features. We observe vibrational effects in the measured spectrum and in the calculations the atomic motion is modeled using the Franck–Condon approximation and the linear coupling model. Our findings show that vibrational effects cannot be neglected in the analysis of high resolution inelastic X-ray scattering spectroscopy. The results also support the validity of the transition potential approximation for calculating core excited state potential energy surfaces.
From Soup: 1 We report non-resonant inelastic X-ray scattering experiments of several gaseous samples in the inner-shell excitation energy range. The experimental near-edge spectra from all the K -edges of N 2 , N 2 O, and CO 2 including the momentum transfer dependence are presented. The results are analyzed using density functional theory calculations that accurately reproduce the experimental spectral features. We observe vibrational effects in the measured spectrum and in the calculations the atomic motion is modeled using the Franck–Condon approximation and the linear coupling model. Our findings show that vibrational effects cannot be neglected in the analysis of high resolution inelastic X-ray scattering spectroscopy . The results also support the validity of the transition potential approximation for calculating core excited state potential energy surfaces.
 ###### 
From cou.: 2 Spectroscopic experiments of gaseous samples provide important information on the atomic and electronic structure and dynamics as well as chemical processes of molecules. Infrared, optical and X-ray core-level spectroscopies are nowadays widely used experimental tools for such studies. Non-resonant inelastic X-ray scattering (NRIXS) has potential to overcome many challenges that may obscure the applicability of the above mentioned techniques. In particular, due to the penetrating power of the high energy X-rays used in NRIXS, the experiments can be carried out using elaborate, e.g. visibly opaque, sample cells.1 This makes it possible to carry out the measurements at extreme temperatures and pressures and thus in environments simulating e.g. upper or extraterrestrial atmospheres. Another appealing feature of the technique is that it can be used to obtain information on the ionic and electronic response in a wide energy range, i.e. from the infrared to hard X-ray energies. Moreover, the momentum transfer dependence (probed via changing the scattering angle) can provide a comprehensive picture of the excitations beyond the dipole selection rule.2
From Soup: 2 Spectroscopic experiments of gaseous samples provide important information on the atomic and electronic structure and dynamics as well as chemical processes of molecules. Infrared, optical and X-ray core-level spectroscopies are nowadays widely used experimental tools for such studies. Non-resonant inelastic X-ray scattering ( NRIXS ) has potential to overcome many challenges that may obscure the applicability of the above mentioned techniques. In particular, due to the penetrating power of the high energy X-rays used in NRIXS , the experiments can be carried out using elaborate, e.g. visibly opaque, sample cells. 1 This makes it possible to carry out the measurements at extreme temperatures and pressures and thus in environments simulating e.g. upper or extraterrestrial atmospheres. Another appealing feature of the technique is that it can be used to obtain information on the ionic and electronic response in a wide energy range, i.e. from the infrared to hard X-ray energies. Moreover, the momentum transfer dependence (probed via changing the scattering angle) can provide a comprehensive picture of the excitations beyond the dipole selection rule. 2
 ###### 
From cou.: 3 The present work aims towards a new in situ spectroscopic method that can access information on the electronic structure and dynamics of chemically relevant molecules. In combination with reliable computational methods this could open possibilities for the characterization of chemical reaction paths and mechanisms. Future developments and studies of vibrationally resolved excitation spectra using NRIXS could yield new applications.
From Soup: 3 The present work aims towards a new in situ spectroscopic method that can access information on the electronic structure and dynamics of chemically relevant molecules. In combination with reliable computational methods this could open possibilities for the characterization of chemical reaction paths and mechanisms. Future developments and studies of vibrationally resolved excitation spectra using NRIXS could yield new applications.
 ###### 
From cou.: 4 In the NRIXS process a high energy (typically around 10 keV) X-ray photon scatters from the sample so that energy ℏω and momentum ℏq are transferred to the target material. This causes an elementary excitation in the sample, such as electronic transition or induced atomic motion. Since one probes the scattering intensity as a function of the energy transfer, the NRIXS spectrum can be measured for the whole energy range below the incident photon energy. The double differential cross section corresponding to the scattering intensity to the solid angle element [Ω, Ω + dΩ] and energy transfer interval ℏ[ω, ω + dω] can be written within the first Born approximation as where is the Thomson scattering cross section and S(q, ω) is the dynamic structure factor that contains all the structural information of the sample material that can be obtained by NRIXS.1 In this work we focus on the part of the spectrum where excitations of core-level electrons can be probed, i.e. X-ray Raman scattering (XRS).
From Soup: 4 In the NRIXS process a high energy (typically around 10 keV) X-ray photon scatters from the sample so that energy ℏ ω and momentum ℏ q are transferred to the target material. This causes an elementary excitation in the sample, such as electronic transition or induced atomic motion. Since one probes the scattering intensity as a function of the energy transfer, the NRIXS spectrum can be measured for the whole energy range below the incident photon energy. The double differential cross section corresponding to the scattering intensity to the solid angle element [ Ω , Ω + d Ω ] and energy transfer interval ℏ[ ω , ω + d ω ] can be written within the first Born approximation as where is the Thomson scattering cross section and S ( q , ω ) is the dynamic structure factor that contains all the structural information of the sample material that can be obtained by NRIXS . 1 In this work we focus on the part of the spectrum where excitations of core-level electrons can be probed, i.e. X-ray Raman scattering ( XRS ).
 ###### 
From cou.: 5 Like other widely used core-level spectroscopies, such as X-ray absorption (XAS) and electron energy-loss (EELS) spectroscopy, XRS is used to study the atomic and electronic structure of a wide range of different materials. The low cross section has obscured the use of NRIXS for samples with low electron density, and most XRS studies have therefore focused on liquids and solids.3–17 Nevertheless, during the last few years developments in synchrotron radiation instrumentation18,19 have extended the feasibility of the technique to new materials, phases, and experimental conditions. Experiments for gaseous samples have become feasible for sample cells where relatively high gas pressures can be realized.20–22 In this work we demonstrate the technique for the nitrogen, oxygen, and carbonK-edges of gaseous N2, N2O, and CO2. The observed electronic transitions for these gases are relatively well-known and their energies and molecular orbital assignments have been presented in the literature.23–27 We carried out new calculations with two objectives: to model the momentum transfer dependence of the spectral features and to account for the vibrational effects. Accurate simulations are valuable for the unambiguous interpretation of the experimental spectra.
From Soup: 5 Like other widely used core-level spectroscopies, such as X-ray absorption ( XAS ) and electron energy-loss ( EELS ) spectroscopy , XRS is used to study the atomic and electronic structure of a wide range of different materials. The low cross section has obscured the use of NRIXS for samples with low electron density, and most XRS studies have therefore focused on liquids and solids. 3–17 Nevertheless, during the last few years developments in synchrotron radiation instrumentation 18,19 have extended the feasibility of the technique to new materials, phases, and experimental conditions. Experiments for gaseous samples have become feasible for sample cells where relatively high gas pressures can be realized. 20–22 In this work we demonstrate the technique for the nitrogen , oxygen, and carbon K -edges of gaseous N 2 , N 2 O, and CO 2 . The observed electronic transitions for these gases are relatively well-known and their energies and molecular orbital assignments have been presented in the literature. 23–27 We carried out new calculations with two objectives: to model the momentum transfer dependence of the spectral features and to account for the vibrational effects. Accurate simulations are valuable for the unambiguous interpretation of the experimental spectra.
 ###### 
From cou.: 6 The NRIXS experiment was carried out at beamline ID16 of the European Synchrotron Radiation Facility (ESRF).19 The sample chamber was constructed from a commercially available quartz capillary (Hilgenberg GmbH) having a diameter of 2 mm and a wall thickness of 10 μm. The capillary was reinforced with a thin layer of epoxy, except for a 20 mm strip near the top of the capillary. The incident beam and scattered radiation passed through this non-coated part. The open end of the capillary was epoxy glued to a short stainless steel pipe, which in turn was connected to the gas lines using standard Swagelok fittings. A static and stable pressure of 40 bar could be consistently reached using this setup.
From Soup: 6 The NRIXS experiment was carried out at beamline ID16 of the European Synchrotron Radiation Facility (ESRF). 19 The sample chamber was constructed from a commercially available quartz capillary (Hilgenberg GmbH) having a diameter of 2 mm and a wall thickness of 10 μm. The capillary was reinforced with a thin layer of epoxy, except for a 20 mm strip near the top of the capillary. The incident beam and scattered radiation passed through this non-coated part. The open end of the capillary was epoxy glued to a short stainless steel pipe, which in turn was connected to the gas lines using standard Swagelok fittings. A static and stable pressure of 40 bar could be consistently reached using this setup.
 ###### 
From cou.: 7 We employed additional gas valves situated closely before and after the capillary. In order to guarantee the purity of the sample, the capillary was evacuated to vacuum and pressurised several times before commencing with the data collection. All valves were kept closed during data collection in order to constrict gas leak in case of capillary failure. The gas samples were obtained from Air Liquide with the minimum purity of 99.99% and used without further purification.
From Soup: 7 We employed additional gas valves situated closely before and after the capillary. In order to guarantee the purity of the sample, the capillary was evacuated to vacuum and pressurised several times before commencing with the data collection. All valves were kept closed during data collection in order to constrict gas leak in case of capillary failure. The gas samples were obtained from Air Liquide with the minimum purity of 99.99% and used without further purification .
 ###### 
From cou.: 8 Monochromatized incident radiation was used and the scattered radiation was analyzed using a multianalyzer crystal array employing the Si (660) reflection. The data were collected individually from each analyzer crystal using a Medipix2 pixel detector. Due to the nearly point-to-point focussing optics of the analyzer crystals and the use of the 2D detector, scattering from gas within the capillary and from the quartz capillary walls could be readily discriminated (see Fig. 1).28
From Soup: 8 Monochromatized incident radiation was used and the scattered radiation was analyzed using a multianalyzer crystal array employing the Si (660) reflection. The data were collected individually from each analyzer crystal using a Medipix2 pixel detector . Due to the nearly point-to-point focussing optics of the analyzer crystals and the use of the 2D detector, scattering from gas within the capillary and from the quartz capillary walls could be readily discriminated (see Fig. 1 ). 28
 ###### 
From cou.: 9 With the incident energy of 9.68 keV, a total energy resolution of 0.5 eV was measured from the full width at half maximum of the elastic line. In order to increase the total irradiated gas volume, the capillary was positioned so that its long axis made an angle of 30° with the incident beam. The sample gas pressure was 35 bar and the measurement time for a single spectrum was approximately 10 h.
From Soup: 9 With the incident energy of 9.68 keV, a total energy resolution of 0.5 eV was measured from the full width at half maximum of the elastic line. In order to increase the total irradiated gas volume, the capillary was positioned so that its long axis made an angle of 30° with the incident beam. The sample gas pressure was 35 bar and the measurement time for a single spectrum was approximately 10 h.
 ###### 
From cou.: 10 The XRS spectra for each sample were collected with 9 different analyzers at two average scattering angles (30° and 137°) of the multianalyzer setup, yielding 9 low-q and 9 high-qspectra for each sample. A constant background was subtracted from the low-qspectrum. From the high-qspectrum a Compton background was subtracted by approximating the part of the Compton profile below the edge by a Pearson VII function.29,30 The momentum transfer dependence was found to be small within the q-range covered by the analyzer array at a fixed value of the mean scattering angle. Therefore the data from each analyzer were summed together to yield a single low-qspectrum with a momentum transfer of 2.8 ± 0.7 Å−1. The high-qspectra were similarly averaged and thus a spectrum with the momentum transfer of 9.4 ± 0.3 Å−1 was extracted.
From Soup: 10 The XRS spectra for each sample were collected with 9 different analyzers at two average scattering angles (30° and 137°) of the multianalyzer setup, yielding 9 low- q and 9 high- q spectra for each sample. A constant background was subtracted from the low- q spectrum. From the high- q spectrum a Compton background was subtracted by approximating the part of the Compton profile below the edge by a Pearson VII function. 29,30 The momentum transfer dependence was found to be small within the q -range covered by the analyzer array at a fixed value of the mean scattering angle. Therefore the data from each analyzer were summed together to yield a single low- q spectrum with a momentum transfer of 2.8 ± 0.7 Å −1 . The high- q spectra were similarly averaged and thus a spectrum with the momentum transfer of 9.4 ± 0.3 Å −1 was extracted.
