From cou.: 11 According to the Fermi golden rule, the coupling of the electromagnetic field with the electronic system leads to the following expression for the dynamic structure factor:1where the I and F denote all possible initial and final many-particle states of the system, and ωI and ωF are their energies. ρI is the statistical weight of the initial state I. The sum inside the matrix element is over all the electrons in the system. At energy transfers close to the X-ray absorption edges the dynamic structure factor can be usually calculated using a single particle framework where the effect of the core hole is included using, e.g. the transition potential approximation31 (TPA), Z + 1 approximation32 or the final state rule.33 Then the electrons occupy individual orbitals and when the vibrational excitations are neglected the dynamic structure factor becomes where the sums over ie and fe include all the occupied and the unoccupied electronic states, respectively, and ωie and ωfe are their energies (expressed in atomic units throughout this work, except for the numerical values that are given in eVs).34 In K-edge XRS the sum over the initial states is reduced to one term because only transitions from a specific (1s) inner-shell state are probed.
From Soup: 11 According to the Fermi golden rule, the coupling of the electromagnetic field with the electronic system leads to the following expression for the dynamic structure factor: 1 where the I and F denote all possible initial and final many-particle states of the system, and ω I and ω F are their energies. ρ I is the statistical weight of the initial state I . The sum inside the matrix element is over all the electrons in the system. At energy transfers close to the X-ray absorption edges the dynamic structure factor can be usually calculated using a single particle framework where the effect of the core hole is included using, e.g. the transition potential approximation 31 (TPA), Z + 1 approximation 32 or the final state rule. 33 Then the electrons occupy individual orbitals and when the vibrational excitations are neglected the dynamic structure factor becomes where the sums over ie and fe include all the occupied and the unoccupied electronic states, respectively, and ω ie and ω fe are their energies (expressed in atomic units throughout this work, except for the numerical values that are given in eVs). 34 In K -edge XRS the sum over the initial states is reduced to one term because only transitions from a specific (1s) inner-shell state are probed.
