From cou.: 12 The calculation of the electronic properties of the studied system requires the knowledge of its molecular structure. In many applications it is sufficient to calculate the dynamic structure factor for the equilibrium structure (minimum energy configuration) only. The delta peak spectrum from eqn (3) is then broadened using an appropriate broadening scheme. The broadening is typically attributed to the finite lifetime of the excited electronic state, but part of it is also due to the vibrational effects. The vibrations can often be neglected in the analysis if the lifetime broadening (∼100 meV for K-edges of carbon, nitrogen, and oxygen)35 or experimental energy resolution (∼50–1000 meV in XRS) is much larger than the vibrational frequencies of the system (∼10–500 meV). Because the recent developments in the instrumentation have made XRS experiments with high energy resolution possible19–21,36 and because quite different computational approaches exist in the literature37–42 we review here the applicable quantum mechanical treatment for including vibrational effects in the XRS spectra.
From Soup: 12 The calculation of the electronic properties of the studied system requires the knowledge of its molecular structure. In many applications it is sufficient to calculate the dynamic structure factor for the equilibrium structure (minimum energy configuration) only. The delta peak spectrum from eqn (3) is then broadened using an appropriate broadening scheme. The broadening is typically attributed to the finite lifetime of the excited electronic state, but part of it is also due to the vibrational effects. The vibrations can often be neglected in the analysis if the lifetime broadening (∼100 meV for K -edges of carbon, nitrogen , and oxygen) 35 or experimental energy resolution (∼50–1000 meV in XRS ) is much larger than the vibrational frequencies of the system (∼10–500 meV). Because the recent developments in the instrumentation have made XRS experiments with high energy resolution possible 19–21,36 and because quite different computational approaches exist in the literature 37–42 we review here the applicable quantum mechanical treatment for including vibrational effects in the XRS spectra.
 ###### 
From cou.: 13 The vibrational effects appear in the electronic excitation spectra because the interatomic forces are different in the ground and excited electronic states. Quantum mechanically, the final state (|F〉 in eqn (2)) includes an excitation of both electronic and vibrational degrees of freedom, i.e. the vibrational state changes concurrently with the electronic excitation. The harmonic approximation of interatomic potentials is often used to understand and model the vibrational properties of molecules. This approximation enables the formulation of the atomic motion within the occupation number representation of the M vibrational normal modes denoted by the normal coordinates Qj.43 Simultaneously with the electronic excitation (from |ie〉 to |fe〉) the vibrational state changes from the initial state |iv〉 = |n1, n2,…, nM〉 to the final state . At zero temperature the only occupied initial vibrational state is the ground state, i.e. nj = 0 for all normal modes j. At higher temperatures one should consider an ensemble of initial vibrational state vectors where nonzero occupation numbers occur.
From Soup: 13 The vibrational effects appear in the electronic excitation spectra because the interatomic forces are different in the ground and excited electronic states. Quantum mechanically, the final state (| F 〉 in eqn (2) ) includes an excitation of both electronic and vibrational degrees of freedom, i.e. the vibrational state changes concurrently with the electronic excitation. The harmonic approximation of interatomic potentials is often used to understand and model the vibrational properties of molecules. This approximation enables the formulation of the atomic motion within the occupation number representation of the M vibrational normal modes denoted by the normal coordinates Q j . 43 Simultaneously with the electronic excitation (from | ie 〉 to | fe 〉) the vibrational state changes from the initial state | iv 〉 = | n 1 , n 2 ,…, n M 〉 to the final state . At zero temperature the only occupied initial vibrational state is the ground state, i.e. n j = 0 for all normal modes j . At higher temperatures one should consider an ensemble of initial vibrational state vectors where nonzero occupation numbers occur.
 ###### 
From cou.: 14 In the excitation process the vibrational energy changes from in the initial state to in the final state, where ωj and are the eigenfrequencies of the normal mode j in the initial and final states, respectively. When the interatomic forces (or, equivalently, potential energy surfaces) of the initial and final electronic states differ, the equilibrium geometry, normal coordinates, and vibrational frequencies are different in the two electronic states. The energy required for the excitation of the system is then Δωie,iv → fe,fv = ωfe − ωie + ωfv − ωiv, so that vibrational side peaks (fine structure) appear at energies that differ from each other by multiples of the vibrational frequencies.
From Soup: 14 In the excitation process the vibrational energy changes from in the initial state to in the final state, where ω j and are the eigenfrequencies of the normal mode j in the initial and final states, respectively. When the interatomic forces (or, equivalently, potential energy surfaces) of the initial and final electronic states differ, the equilibrium geometry, normal coordinates, and vibrational frequencies are different in the two electronic states. The energy required for the excitation of the system is then Δ ω ie , iv → fe , fv = ω fe − ω ie + ω fv − ω iv , so that vibrational side peaks (fine structure) appear at energies that differ from each other by multiples of the vibrational frequencies.
