From Soup: 39 In principle one should carry out the geometry optimization and normal mode analysis for each electronic final state (denoted by the unoccupied orbitals | fe 〉 in the single-particle picture). Probably the simplest approach for overcoming this cumbersome task is the linear coupling model ( LCM ). In this approximation the normal coordinates and vibrational frequencies are assumed to be the same in excited and ground electronic states, and the only thing that changes is the minimum energy configuration. 45 Despite its simplicity LCM often provides good results. 46,47 A more sophisticated approach is to express the final state vibrations using the initial state normal coordinates through Duschinsky transformation. 48–50 It is also possible to go beyond the harmonic approximation and the normal mode approach. Anharmonic effects can be handled e.g. using Morse potentials. 51 Treatment of double well potential energy surfaces has been described e.g. in ref. 52 . If the final state is dissociative, the vibrational effects can be simulated by the projection of the initial state vibrational wave function onto the final state potential energy surface. 53 An appealing approach is the propagation of nuclear wave packets in explicitly calculated potential energy surfaces. This method is capable of describing both dissociative and bound vibrational transitions. 54,55
 ###### 
From cou.: 40 44
From Soup: 40 The electronic structure calculations in this work were carried out using the StoBe-deMon software that utilizes density functional theory (DFT) and localized Gaussian basis functions. 56 The method for calculating the near-edge spectrum employs TPA to model the relaxation effects of the valence electrons in the presence of the core hole. In this scheme the occupation of the initial one-electron state is set to 0.5. 31,53 We used triple zeta plus valence polarization level basis sets ([1d,3p,4s] contractions from ref. 57 ), except for the excited atomic site for which we used the III-IGLO basis set and an additional set of diffuse basis functions ([25s,25p,25d] uncontracted set using the double basis set technique.). 58,59 Electronic exchange and correlation effects were included in the generalized gradient approximation level. 60,61 When the molecule contained multiple atoms of the same element as the excited one, the localization of the core hole was ensured by using model core potentials for the non-excited atoms. 62
 ###### 
From cou.: 41 In principle one should carry out the geometry optimization and normal mode analysis for each electronic final state (denoted by the unoccupied orbitals |fe〉 in the single-particle picture). Probably the simplest approach for overcoming this cumbersome task is the linear coupling model (LCM). In this approximation the normal coordinates and vibrational frequencies are assumed to be the same in excited and ground electronic states, and the only thing that changes is the minimum energy configuration.45 Despite its simplicity LCM often provides good results.46,47 A more sophisticated approach is to express the final state vibrations using the initial state normal coordinates through Duschinsky transformation.48–50 It is also possible to go beyond the harmonic approximation and the normal mode approach. Anharmonic effects can be handled e.g. using Morse potentials.51 Treatment of double well potential energy surfaces has been described e.g. in ref. 52. If the final state is dissociative, the vibrational effects can be simulated by the projection of the initial state vibrational wave function onto the final state potential energy surface.53 An appealing approach is the propagation of nuclear wave packets in explicitly calculated potential energy surfaces. This method is capable of describing both dissociative and bound vibrational transitions.54,55
From Soup: 41 The first step in our calculations was to determine the ground state structure by a geometry optimization routine, and then to solve the vibrational eigenmodes and frequencies (see Table 1 ). The XRS matrix elements M ie , fe ( q ) and transition energies ω fe − ω ie were calculated for the ground state configurations ( Q = 0) as described in ref. 34 . To include the vibrational effects in the excitation spectrum we use the LCM, which is a crude approximation especially for N 2 O and CO 2 (as discussed later) but nevertheless useful for the illustration of the effect. It also provides surprisingly good results here. As mentioned above, within LCM the normal coordinates remain unchanged in the electronic transition and the only thing that changes is the minimum energy configuration. These are calculated from the slope of the final state potential energy surfaces at the ground state geometry. For this purpose we carried out calculations for three configurations where the coordinates were slightly shifted in the direction of the normal coordinate vectors. These provide the derivatives of the final state potential energy surfaces, i.e. ∂ ω fe / ∂ Q v | Q v =0 , which in turn are required to calculate the Franck–Condon overlap integrals 〈 fv | iv 〉 63,64 and the minimum of the potential energy surface of the final electronic state ( i.e. ω fe ). The vibrational calculations were only carried out for the lowest transitions that are also the most pronounced ones in the XRS spectra.
 ###### 
From cou.: 42 The electronic structure calculations in this work were carried out using the StoBe-deMon software that utilizes density functional theory (DFT) and localized Gaussian basis functions.56 The method for calculating the near-edge spectrum employs TPA to model the relaxation effects of the valence electrons in the presence of the core hole. In this scheme the occupation of the initial one-electron state is set to 0.5.31,53 We used triple zeta plus valence polarization level basis sets ([1d,3p,4s] contractions from ref. 57), except for the excited atomic site for which we used the III-IGLO basis set and an additional set of diffuse basis functions ([25s,25p,25d] uncontracted set using the double basis set technique.).58,59 Electronic exchange and correlation effects were included in the generalized gradient approximation level.60,61 When the molecule contained multiple atoms of the same element as the excited one, the localization of the core hole was ensured by using model core potentials for the non-excited atoms.62
From Soup: 42 The dynamic structure factor can then be calculated using eqn (4) and (5) . We used the temperature of 300 K to generate the sets of vibrational state vectors | iv 〉 for the initial state and the corresponding weights ρ iv according to the Boltzmann statistics. The number of included initial states was chosen using the condition ∑ iv ρ iv > 99%. Most vibrational transitions give negligible contribution to the XRS spectrum, and therefore only the most significant ones were included in our calculations. Using the completeness relations of Franck–Condon overlap integrals, we ensured that more than 98% of the intensity is included in the calculation.
 ###### 
From cou.: 43 The first step in our calculations was to determine the ground state structure by a geometry optimization routine, and then to solve the vibrational eigenmodes and frequencies (see Table 1). The XRS matrix elements Mie,fe(q) and transition energies ωfe − ωie were calculated for the ground state configurations (Q = 0) as described in ref. 34. To include the vibrational effects in the excitation spectrum we use the LCM, which is a crude approximation especially for N2O and CO2 (as discussed later) but nevertheless useful for the illustration of the effect. It also provides surprisingly good results here. As mentioned above, within LCM the normal coordinates remain unchanged in the electronic transition and the only thing that changes is the minimum energy configuration. These are calculated from the slope of the final state potential energy surfaces at the ground state geometry. For this purpose we carried out calculations for three configurations where the coordinates were slightly shifted in the direction of the normal coordinate vectors. These provide the derivatives of the final state potential energy surfaces, i.e. ∂ωfe/∂Qv|Qv=0, which in turn are required to calculate the Franck–Condon overlap integrals 〈fv|iv〉63,64 and the minimum of the potential energy surface of the final electronic state (i.e. ωfe). The vibrational calculations were only carried out for the lowest transitions that are also the most pronounced ones in the XRS spectra.
From Soup: 43 The calculated XRS spectrum consists of a set of delta peaks because the finite lifetime of the electronic excitations is not accounted for in our approach (except for dissociative transitions, see below). The delta peak spectra were broadened using a Lorentzian linewidth whose energy dependence is given in Table 2 . Despite the lack of a proper justification this kind of scheme is commonly employed to facilitate the comparison with experiment. 34 To align the calculated spectra with experimental results, rigid energy shifts of approximately 1 eV (see Table 2 ) were applied. We also used Gaussian convolution with FWHM = 0.5 eV in order to take the instrumental resolution of the experiment into account.
 ###### 
From cou.: 44 The dynamic structure factor can then be calculated using eqn (4) and (5). We used the temperature of 300 K to generate the sets of vibrational state vectors |iv〉 for the initial state and the corresponding weights ρiv according to the Boltzmann statistics. The number of included initial states was chosen using the condition ∑ivρiv > 99%. Most vibrational transitions give negligible contribution to the XRS spectrum, and therefore only the most significant ones were included in our calculations. Using the completeness relations of Franck–Condon overlap integrals, we ensured that more than 98% of the intensity is included in the calculation.
From Soup: 44 The lineshape of the one dissociative transition (observed in the oxygen K -edge spectrum of N 2 O) was approximated by a Lorentzian whose FWHM was obtained by projecting the initial state vibrational wave function onto the final state potential energy surface along the dissociative mode's normal coordinate Q v . 53 In the case of a linear potential energy surface the result is a Gaussian and the , where σ 2 v is the variance of the initial state vibrational wave function.
 ###### 
From cou.: 45 The calculated XRS spectrum consists of a set of delta peaks because the finite lifetime of the electronic excitations is not accounted for in our approach (except for dissociative transitions, see below). The delta peak spectra were broadened using a Lorentzian linewidth whose energy dependence is given in Table 2. Despite the lack of a proper justification this kind of scheme is commonly employed to facilitate the comparison with experiment.34 To align the calculated spectra with experimental results, rigid energy shifts of approximately 1 eV (see Table 2) were applied. We also used Gaussian convolution with FWHM = 0.5 eV in order to take the instrumental resolution of the experiment into account.
From Soup: 45 Here we present the experimental q -dependent XRS near-edge spectra together with comparisons to calculations. Each pair of theoretical and experimental spectra are normalized to equal integrated area, and all main features are denoted by capital letters to help comparison. The momentum transfer dependence generally makes the identification of the experimental features easier as the symmetry properties of the corresponding final electronic states can be distinguished. 2 It therefore facilitates the assignment of the experimental and calculated features. The vibrational fine structure was calculated for all denoted transitions.
