From cou.: 46 The lineshape of the one dissociative transition (observed in the oxygenK-edge spectrum of N2O) was approximated by a Lorentzian whose FWHM was obtained by projecting the initial state vibrational wave function onto the final state potential energy surface along the dissociative mode's normal coordinate Qv.53 In the case of a linear potential energy surface the result is a Gaussian and the , where σ2v is the variance of the initial state vibrational wave function.
From Soup: 46 The experimental and calculated K -edge spectra for N 2 are shown in Fig. 2 . The momentum transfer dependence of the spectral features is well reproduced by the calculation. Feature A at 401 eV is the preionization peak that corresponds to the transition to the antibonding π-type state. Its measured momentum transfer dependence is in line with previously published EELS results. 65 Features B and C are assigned to the 3sσ and 3pπ Rydberg states, respectively. 25 The pronounced s-type character increases the intensity of feature B at high momentum transfer.
 ###### 
From cou.: 47 Here we present the experimental q-dependent XRS near-edge spectra together with comparisons to calculations. Each pair of theoretical and experimental spectra are normalized to equal integrated area, and all main features are denoted by capital letters to help comparison. The momentum transfer dependence generally makes the identification of the experimental features easier as the symmetry properties of the corresponding final electronic states can be distinguished.2 It therefore facilitates the assignment of the experimental and calculated features. The vibrational fine structure was calculated for all denoted transitions.
From Soup: 47 The experimental and computational spectra for the nitrogen and oxygen K -edges of N 2 O are shown in Fig. 3 . The overall agreement is again strong, and the calculation reproduces the momentum transfer dependence of all the main features A–H. In contrast to N 2 , two main transitions (features A and B) appear in the nitrogen K -edge of N 2 O due to the different chemical surroundings of the two nitrogens in the molecule (N–N–O). Peak A originates from the excitation of the atom at the end of the molecule, and feature B originates from the central nitrogen . In both cases the transition is from 1s to a π-type state, similarly to the N 2 spectrum. The low-energy shoulder of feature B also contains a small peak that is not clearly resolved with the present experimental energy resolution. It has been distinguished in various previous works 23,66 and is also reproduced in our calculations. This and feature C are due to the transitions from terminal nitrogen to 3sσ and 4sσ states, respectively. 23 Similarly, features D and E get their intensity mostly from the corresponding transitions of the central nitrogen , although at this energy range also numerous Rydberg-type final states contribute slightly. The q -dependence of these features, which is also reproduced by our calculations, facilitates the assignment.
 ###### 
From cou.: 48 The experimental and calculated K-edge spectra for N2 are shown in Fig. 2. The momentum transfer dependence of the spectral features is well reproduced by the calculation. Feature A at 401 eV is the preionization peak that corresponds to the transition to the antibonding π-type state. Its measured momentum transfer dependence is in line with previously published EELS results.65 Features B and C are assigned to the 3sσ and 3pπ Rydberg states, respectively.25 The pronounced s-type character increases the intensity of feature B at high momentum transfer.
From Soup: 48 The oxygen K -edge spectrum of N 2 O consists of three main features. Feature F again corresponds to the excitation to a π-type final state, and its weight decreases with increasing q . In contrast, feature G becomes more pronounced at large q . The corresponding final electronic state (3sσ) is dissociative 67 and therefore it does not show a vibrational fine structure. The broad feature H has been attributed to various final states, in particular 3pπ, 4sσ, and 5sσ. 23,67 In our calculation it consists almost completely of the 4sσ transition.
 ###### 
From cou.: 49 The experimental and computational spectra for the nitrogen and oxygenK-edges of N2O are shown in Fig. 3. The overall agreement is again strong, and the calculation reproduces the momentum transfer dependence of all the main features A–H. In contrast to N2, two main transitions (features A and B) appear in the nitrogenK-edge of N2O due to the different chemical surroundings of the two nitrogens in the molecule (N–N–O). Peak A originates from the excitation of the atom at the end of the molecule, and feature B originates from the central nitrogen. In both cases the transition is from 1s to a π-type state, similarly to the N2spectrum. The low-energy shoulder of feature B also contains a small peak that is not clearly resolved with the present experimental energy resolution. It has been distinguished in various previous works23,66 and is also reproduced in our calculations. This and feature C are due to the transitions from terminal nitrogen to 3sσ and 4sσ states, respectively.23 Similarly, features D and E get their intensity mostly from the corresponding transitions of the central nitrogen, although at this energy range also numerous Rydberg-type final states contribute slightly. The q-dependence of these features, which is also reproduced by our calculations, facilitates the assignment.
From Soup: 49 The experimental and computational spectra for the carbon and oxygen K -edges of CO 2 are shown in Fig. 4 . Also here the main features (A–F) of the experimental spectra are well reproduced in the calculations. Both strongest peaks (features A and D) correspond to transitions to the lowest-lying π-type final state. The intensities of the peaks B and C of the computational high- q spectrum are slightly overestimated. These features can be assigned to the excitations to the 3sσ state and to several Rydberg states, respectively. 26 Moreover, the calculated low- q spectrum significantly underestimates the intensity of feature B. The reason is that this peak is dipole forbidden and gains its intensity at low q mainly by a vibronic coupling effect 68,69 which is not included in our calculations. Its nonzero intensity in the simulation is only due to the finite momentum transfer value and it would vanish completely at the dipole limit q → 0.
 ###### 
From cou.: 50 The oxygenK-edge spectrum of N2O consists of three main features. Feature F again corresponds to the excitation to a π-type final state, and its weight decreases with increasing q. In contrast, feature G becomes more pronounced at large q. The corresponding final electronic state (3sσ) is dissociative67 and therefore it does not show a vibrational fine structure. The broad feature H has been attributed to various final states, in particular 3pπ, 4sσ, and 5sσ.23,67 In our calculation it consists almost completely of the 4sσ transition.
From Soup: 50 The oxygen K -edge spectrum of CO 2 also contains three main features. Feature E lies in the high-energy shoulder of feature D and corresponds to the 3sσ state. Its weight increases at large q , which can be observed both in the calculation and experiment. The third feature (F) contains transitions to Rydberg-like final states, mainly the ones assigned as 3pσ, 3pπ, and 4sσ in ref. 26 . Contrary to the corresponding feature C in the carbon K -edge spectrum, they have only very weak q -dependence.
 ###### 
From cou.: 51 The experimental and computational spectra for the carbon and oxygenK-edges of CO2 are shown in Fig. 4. Also here the main features (A–F) of the experimental spectra are well reproduced in the calculations. Both strongest peaks (features A and D) correspond to transitions to the lowest-lying π-type final state. The intensities of the peaks B and C of the computational high-qspectrum are slightly overestimated. These features can be assigned to the excitations to the 3sσ state and to several Rydberg states, respectively.26 Moreover, the calculated low-qspectrum significantly underestimates the intensity of feature B. The reason is that this peak is dipole forbidden and gains its intensity at low q mainly by a vibronic coupling effect68,69 which is not included in our calculations. Its nonzero intensity in the simulation is only due to the finite momentum transfer value and it would vanish completely at the dipole limit q → 0.
From Soup: 51 In order to demonstrate the effect of atomic motion on the XRS spectra we compare the dynamic structure factors of N 2 O and CO 2 calculated with and without vibrational effects, i.e. using eqn (4) and (3) , respectively. The result for low q is shown in Fig. 5 . The most significant difference is the vibrational broadening which follows from the distribution of the spectral weight to the various peaks in the fine structure. The vibrational effect would be more prominent at better energy resolution. For instance, the energy of the only vibrational mode of the nitrogen molecule in the core-excited electronic state corresponding to the preionization peak is 0.23 eV. In order to observe the fine structure, energy resolution would need to be smaller than this. 70,71 Such resolution is in fact feasible 19,21,36 and highly desirable for these studies.
 ###### 
From cou.: 52 The oxygenK-edge spectrum of CO2 also contains three main features. Feature E lies in the high-energy shoulder of feature D and corresponds to the 3sσ state. Its weight increases at large q, which can be observed both in the calculation and experiment. The third feature (F) contains transitions to Rydberg-like final states, mainly the ones assigned as 3pσ, 3pπ, and 4sσ in ref. 26. Contrary to the corresponding feature C in the carbonK-edge spectrum, they have only very weak q-dependence.
From Soup: 52 Although the inclusion of the vibrational effects in our calculations improves the agreement with experiment, the simulated lineshapes are not sufficiently broad. This can be attributed to the shortcomings of the linear coupling model, the transition potential approximation, and the harmonic approximation. The broadening is sensitive to the curvature of the potential energy surface, and the resulting features are generally not symmetric. 42,70–73 The asymmetry is observed in the experimental spectra and is also reproduced by our calculations. This is demonstrated in Fig. 6 for the lowest-energy transitions at nitrogen and carbon K -edges of N 2 , N 2 O, and CO 2 . All of these experimental features are clearly asymmetric, with more weight on the high-energy part. The calculations for the vibrational fine structure explain this observation, as also demonstrated in the figure. The calculated result for N 2 is also in line with the experimental, vibrationally resolved spectrum presented in ref. 70 . For N 2 O and CO 2 the calculated vibrational fine structure is separated into two parts according to the two final electronic states that contribute to this transition. In the equilibrium configuration these states are degenerate, but vibrational distortions break the degeneracy into Renner–Teller pair states, and as a result the two states show different vibrational fine structures. 74 Our calculation for CO 2 is in line with the experimental result of ref. 74 . Such good agreement is somewhat surprising because harmonic approximation for the potential energy surface is a very crude model in this case. For a more accurate calculation one should replace the harmonic potential by a double well. 52
 ###### 
From cou.: 53 In order to demonstrate the effect of atomic motion on the XRS spectra we compare the dynamic structure factors of N2O and CO2 calculated with and without vibrational effects, i.e. using eqn (4) and (3), respectively. The result for low q is shown in Fig. 5. The most significant difference is the vibrational broadening which follows from the distribution of the spectral weight to the various peaks in the fine structure. The vibrational effect would be more prominent at better energy resolution. For instance, the energy of the only vibrational mode of the nitrogen molecule in the core-excited electronic state corresponding to the preionization peak is 0.23 eV. In order to observe the fine structure, energy resolution would need to be smaller than this.70,71 Such resolution is in fact feasible19,21,36 and highly desirable for these studies.
From Soup: 53 The accuracy of the present calculations for the vibrational effects is promising because we make several approximations whose accuracy can be questioned. First of all, LCM is in many cases a good scheme but its use might not be fully justified for transitions to states with significantly different vibrational properties compared to the ground state. It is also clear that the harmonic approximation for the potential energy surfaces is not always valid. This is also the case for some core-excited final states of N 2 O and CO 2 , as mentioned earlier. Furthermore, the transition energies and intensities are calculated using TPA, but it is not well known if this method provides reliable potential energy surfaces. In order to get a better understanding of the accuracy of the used approximations, we carried out presumably more accurate ΔKS calculations for the fine structure of the preionization peak of N 2 ( Fig. 6(a) ). In this method the excited state potential energy is calculated from the total energy difference between the initial (ground) and final states (an electron removed from the core state and added to the LUMO). ΔKS is theoretically a better justified method than TPA for calculating the transition energies of the lowest-lying core-excited states, but its application for high-lying transitions is not as straightforward. Because of the two electronic states with different vibrational response involved in N 2 O and CO 2 , we did not carry out ΔKS calculations for these molecules. Nevertheless, for N 2 the resulting vibrational fine structure was very similar to that obtained with TPA. This suggests that TPA can be used to calculate the curvatures of the core excited state potential energy surfaces. The conclusion is also supported by our calculations for N 2 O where we found very similar curvatures of the potential energy surfaces as previously calculated using the configuration interaction method. 67
 ###### 
From cou.: 54 Although the inclusion of the vibrational effects in our calculations improves the agreement with experiment, the simulated lineshapes are not sufficiently broad. This can be attributed to the shortcomings of the linear coupling model, the transition potential approximation, and the harmonic approximation. The broadening is sensitive to the curvature of the potential energy surface, and the resulting features are generally not symmetric.42,70–73 The asymmetry is observed in the experimental spectra and is also reproduced by our calculations. This is demonstrated in Fig. 6 for the lowest-energy transitions at nitrogen and carbonK-edges of N2, N2O, and CO2. All of these experimental features are clearly asymmetric, with more weight on the high-energy part. The calculations for the vibrational fine structure explain this observation, as also demonstrated in the figure. The calculated result for N2 is also in line with the experimental, vibrationally resolved spectrum presented in ref. 70. For N2O and CO2 the calculated vibrational fine structure is separated into two parts according to the two final electronic states that contribute to this transition. In the equilibrium configuration these states are degenerate, but vibrational distortions break the degeneracy into Renner–Teller pair states, and as a result the two states show different vibrational fine structures.74 Our calculation for CO2 is in line with the experimental result of ref. 74. Such good agreement is somewhat surprising because harmonic approximation for the potential energy surface is a very crude model in this case. For a more accurate calculation one should replace the harmonic potential by a double well.52
From Soup: 54 We present the momentum transfer dependent XRS spectra at the K -edges of gaseous nitrogen , nitrous oxide , and carbon dioxide. The experimental results are analyzed using a density functional theory based method that accurately reproduces the main features of the experimental spectra and their momentum transfer dependence. We show how the vibrational effects can be included in the calculation and demonstrate that they are essential for the correct interpretation of the data. In particular, we report the asymmetry of several peaks in the experimental spectra, and explain this in terms of the simultaneous excitation of electronic and vibrational states. Our calculations suggest that the transition potential approximation is an applicable method for calculating the core excited state potential energy surfaces in these cases. This finding is important because TPA is a computationally tractable method and in particular it enables calculating various excited states simultaneously. The linear coupling model that was used for simulating the vibrational effects is a powerful method but has certain limitations. In particular it produces inaccurate results when the harmonic approximation for the potential energy surface is not valid, e.g. for dissociative transitions (like the 3sσ transition in the oxygen K -edge spectrum of N 2 O). More accurate calculations involve going beyond LCM by including Duschinsky rotations 48–50 and loosening the harmonic approximation. 51,52,55 Another possible improvement is the inclusion of vibronic coupling effects. 68,69,75 Furthermore, especially for larger molecules it could be useful to employ the continuum model for the vibrational effects. 76
 ###### 
From cou.: 55 The accuracy of the present calculations for the vibrational effects is promising because we make several approximations whose accuracy can be questioned. First of all, LCM is in many cases a good scheme but its use might not be fully justified for transitions to states with significantly different vibrational properties compared to the ground state. It is also clear that the harmonic approximation for the potential energy surfaces is not always valid. This is also the case for some core-excited final states of N2O and CO2, as mentioned earlier. Furthermore, the transition energies and intensities are calculated using TPA, but it is not well known if this method provides reliable potential energy surfaces. In order to get a better understanding of the accuracy of the used approximations, we carried out presumably more accurate ΔKS calculations for the fine structure of the preionization peak of N2 (Fig. 6(a)). In this method the excited state potential energy is calculated from the total energy difference between the initial (ground) and final states (an electron removed from the core state and added to the LUMO). ΔKS is theoretically a better justified method than TPA for calculating the transition energies of the lowest-lying core-excited states, but its application for high-lying transitions is not as straightforward. Because of the two electronic states with different vibrational response involved in N2O and CO2, we did not carry out ΔKS calculations for these molecules. Nevertheless, for N2 the resulting vibrational fine structure was very similar to that obtained with TPA. This suggests that TPA can be used to calculate the curvatures of the core excited state potential energy surfaces. The conclusion is also supported by our calculations for N2O where we found very similar curvatures of the potential energy surfaces as previously calculated using the configuration interaction method.67
From Soup: 55 The present results show that inelastic X-ray scattering is a powerful spectroscopic tool also for gaseous samples. The exceptional properties of this technique open up new possibilities for the study of chemically relevant molecules and their reactions. The momentum transfer dependence reveals the symmetry properties of the observed transitions and thus facilitates their assignment with corresponding electronic states. Improved energy resolution will also enable measurements of vibrationally resolved excitation spectra . Due to the good penetration of hard X-rays, elaborate sample cells can be utilized to carry out experiments under elevated temperatures and pressures, thus providing an emergent tool for in situ spectroscopic experiments.
 ###### 
From cou.: 56 We present the momentum transfer dependent XRS spectra at the K-edges of gaseous nitrogen, nitrous oxide, and carbon dioxide. The experimental results are analyzed using a density functional theory based method that accurately reproduces the main features of the experimental spectra and their momentum transfer dependence. We show how the vibrational effects can be included in the calculation and demonstrate that they are essential for the correct interpretation of the data. In particular, we report the asymmetry of several peaks in the experimental spectra, and explain this in terms of the simultaneous excitation of electronic and vibrational states. Our calculations suggest that the transition potential approximation is an applicable method for calculating the core excited state potential energy surfaces in these cases. This finding is important because TPA is a computationally tractable method and in particular it enables calculating various excited states simultaneously. The linear coupling model that was used for simulating the vibrational effects is a powerful method but has certain limitations. In particular it produces inaccurate results when the harmonic approximation for the potential energy surface is not valid, e.g. for dissociative transitions (like the 3sσ transition in the oxygenK-edge spectrum of N2O). More accurate calculations involve going beyond LCM by including Duschinsky rotations48–50 and loosening the harmonic approximation.51,52,55 Another possible improvement is the inclusion of vibronic coupling effects.68,69,75 Furthermore, especially for larger molecules it could be useful to employ the continuum model for the vibrational effects.76
