From cou.: 57 The present results show that inelastic X-ray scattering is a powerful spectroscopic tool also for gaseous samples. The exceptional properties of this technique open up new possibilities for the study of chemically relevant molecules and their reactions. The momentum transfer dependence reveals the symmetry properties of the observed transitions and thus facilitates their assignment with corresponding electronic states. Improved energy resolution will also enable measurements of vibrationally resolved excitation spectra. Due to the good penetration of hard X-rays, elaborate sample cells can be utilized to carry out experiments under elevated temperatures and pressures, thus providing an emergent tool for in situ spectroscopic experiments.
